(In reply to Mark Millard from comment #4)

Looking into this again, my attribution of the code/number
for the call being from the instruction encoding was wrong.
It is from r0. It appears that the number in the svc (or
svclt) instruction encoding is ignored.

In other words: using __asm("svclt #0x654321") did not
gets its value from the 0x654321 at all. But
syscall(0x654321,0x123456,0x214365,0x342156) got its
figure from its. 0x654321 (and uses svc #0).

For the syscall:
ktrace/kdump reported 17185, decimal for 0x4321.
truss reported 6636321, decimal for 0x654321.

I'll note for later comparison what the kdump
text looks like:

 61018 a.out    CALL  [17185]
 61018 a.out    RET   [17185] -1 errno 78 Function not implemented

Note that it shows the adjusted number in
the []'s.

Using the following to show sign behavior for
ktrace/kdump:

#include <unistd.h>

int main()
{
        //__asm("svclt #0x654321");
        syscall(0x658321,0x123456,0x214365,0x342156);
}

ktrace/kdump reported -31967, decimal for 0xFFFF8321 (2's complement, 32-bit).
truss reported 6652705, decimal for 0x658321.

Changing to a value to show truss's sign
handling (but not ktrace/kdump's sign
handling):

#include <unistd.h>

int main()
{
        //__asm("svclt #0x654321");
        syscall(0x87654321,0x123456,0x214365,0x342156);
}

ktrace/kdump reported 17185, decimal for 0x4321.
truss reported -2023406815, decimal for 0x87654321 (2's complement, 32-bit).

Of course there are also cases where the
truncation by ktrace/kdump makes things look
okay for the value displayed:

#include <unistd.h>

int main()
{
        //__asm("svclt #0x654321");
        syscall(0x87650021,0x123456,0x214365,0x342156);
}

ktrace/kdump (no number reported at all):

 60996 a.out    CALL  access
 60996 a.out    RET   access -1 errno 78 Function not implemented

truss:

-- UNKNOWN FreeBSD SYSCALL -2023423967 --
#-2023423967()                                   ERR#78 'Function not implemented'

-2023423967 is decimal for 0x87650021 (2's complement, 32-bit).
